{"title_page": "Flag of Blackbeard", "text_new": "{{Infobox flag\n| Name =Blackbeard\n| Article = \n| Image = Pirate Flag of Blackbeard (Edward Teach).svg\n| size  = 200px\n| Alt = \n| Noborder = <!-- Leave blank for rectangular flag; for non-rectangular flag, type \"no\". -->\n| Nickname = Flag of Blackbeard\n| Morenicks = \n| Use = {{FIAV|noflag}}\n| Symbol = \n| Proportion = 3\u00d72\n| Adoption = \n| Relinquished = \n| Design = A black banner with a devil holding an hourglass in his right hand and a spear in his left, using the spear to poke at a red heart dripping three red drops of blood\n| Designer = \n}}\nThe purported '''flag of Blackbeard''', consisting of a horned skeleton using a spear to pierce a bleeding heart, is typically attributed to the pirate Edward Teach, better known as [[Blackbeard]]. However, contrary to [[popular belief]], there is no accurate description of any specific flag used by Blackbeard during his piracy beyond using black flags or \"bloody flags\"<ref name=nc>{{cite web|url=https://www.qaronline.org/blog/2017-10-06/did-you-know-blackbeards-flag|title=Did You Know Blackbeard's Flag is a Modern Design? |website=Queen Anne's Revenge Project |accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> and, in any case, the \"flag of Blackbeard\" appears to be an early 20th-century design.<ref name=mf/>\n\n== History ==\nDuring the [[Golden Age of Piracy]], Blackbeard was one of the most infamous pirates on the seas. The only record there is of what flag he flew was in 1718 in a newspaper report which stated that Blackbeard's fleet, including his flagship ''[[Queen Anne's Revenge]]'', during an attack on the ''Protestant Caesar'' flew black flags with death heads and \"bloody flags\".<ref name=mf /> However it did not state which ship Blackbeard was on at the time.<ref>{{cite book | first =Baylus | last =Brooks |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R39dDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT311&dq=%22Bloody+Flags%22+blackbeard&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5tpb72PLeAhWsI8AKHdsEC0sQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Bloody+Flags%22+blackbeard&f=false |title=Quest for Blackbeard: The True Story of Edward Thache and His World | publisher = Lulu Press | volume =  | year = 2017 | isbn = 1365795926}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a revival in interest in piracy in the 20th century, the flag first appeared in an article in ''[[The Mariner's Mirror]]'' magazine as a general pirate's flag in 1912 but the article made no assertion of it being Blackbeard's flag.<ref name=nc /> Later in the century approximately around the 1970s it started to be ascribed as Blackbeard's flag and was often used as such in books and television programmes portraying him.<ref name=mf>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/531982/facts-about-pirate-blackbeard|title=15 Facts About Blackbeard|date=22 November 2018|website=Mental Floss|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n[[File:Pirate Death's Head Flag.svg|thumb|According to sources, Blackbeard flew a black flag with a skull on it along with a blood red flag rather than the devil flag.]]\nThe design of the flag consisted of a horned skeleton raising an hourglass \"toasting the Devil\" in its right hand.<ref name=nc /> In the skeleton's left hand, it held a spear pointing towards a red heart which had three drops of red blood below it, supposedly to signal that no quarter would be given.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/famous-pirates-and-their-flags-2136233|title=Who Are History's Most Famous Pirates and Their Flags?|first=Christopher |last=Minster |website=ThoughtCo|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> The historian E. T. Fox affirmed that this flag design would not have been of 18th-century pirate origin because, if the skeleton was meant to represent the Devil, then it would not have been a skeleton, and if it was supposed to represent [[Death (personification)|Death]], then it would not have been horned.<ref name=nc /> Most pirate flags at the time would have used simple imagery based on Christian symbols of mortality.<Ref name=nc />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Jolly Roger]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* Fox, E.T. (2015). ''Jolly Rogers, the True History of Pirate Flags''. {{ISBN|978-1-326-44817-2}}\n\n[[Category:Piracy]]\n[[Category:Maritime flags]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox flag\n| Name =Blackbeard\n| Article = \n| Image = Pirate Flag of Blackbeard (Edward Teach).svg\n| size  = 200px\n| Alt = \n| Noborder = <!-- Leave blank for rectangular flag; for non-rectangular flag, type \"no\". -->\n| Nickname = Flag of Blackbeard\n| Morenicks = \n| Use = {{FIAV|noflag}}\n| Symbol = \n| Proportion = 3\u00d72\n| Adoption = \n| Relinquished = \n| Design = A black banner with a devil holding an hourglass in his right hand and a spear in his left, using the spear to poke at a red heart dripping three red drops of blood\n| Designer = \n}}\nThe purported '''flag of Blackbeard''', consisting of a horned skeleton using a spear to pierce a bleeding heart, is typically attributed to the pirate Edward Teach, better known as [[Blackbeard]]. However, contrary to [[popular belief]], there is no accurate description of any specific flag used by Blackbeard during his piracy beyond using black flags or \"bloody flags\"<ref name=nc>{{cite web|url=https://www.qaronline.org/blog/2017-10-06/did-you-know-blackbeards-flag|title=Did You Know Blackbeard's Flag is a Modern Design? |website=Queen Anne's Revenge Project |accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> and, in any case, the \"flag of Blackbeard\" appears to be an early 20th-century design.<ref name=mf/>\n\n== History ==\nDuring the [[Golden Age of Piracy]], Blackbeard was one of the most infamous pirates on the seas. The only record there is of what flag he flew was in 1718 in a newspaper report which stated that Blackbeard's fleet, including his flagship ''[[Queen Anne's Revenge]]'', during an attack on the ''Protestant Caesar'' flew black flags with death heads and \"bloody flags\".<ref name=mf /> However it did not state which ship Blackbeard was on at the time.<ref>{{cite book | first =Baylus | last =Brooks |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R39dDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT311&dq=%22Bloody+Flags%22+blackbeard&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5tpb72PLeAhWsI8AKHdsEC0sQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Bloody+Flags%22+blackbeard&f=false |title=Quest for Blackbeard: The True Story of Edward Thache and His World | publisher = Lulu Press | volume =  | year = 2017 | isbn = 1365795926}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a revival in interest in piracy in the 20th century, the flag first appeared in an article in ''[[The Mariner's Mirror]]'' magazine as a general pirate's flag in 1912 but the article made no assertion of it being Blackbeard's flag.<ref name=nc /> Later in the century approximately around the 1970s it started to be ascribed as Blackbeard's flag and was often used as such in books and television programmes portraying him.<ref name=mf>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/531982/facts-about-pirate-blackbeard|title=15 Facts About Blackbeard|date=22 November 2018|website=Mental Floss|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> Some academic institutions such as the [[Smithsonian]] have also incorrectly described it as the flag of Blackbeard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ocean.si.edu/human-connections/history-cultures/blackbeards-pirate-flag|title=Blackbeard\u2019s Pirate Flag|website=Smithsonian Ocean|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n[[File:Pirate Death's Head Flag.svg|thumb|According to sources, Blackbeard flew a black flag with a skull on it along with a blood red flag rather than the devil flag.]]\nThe design of the flag consisted of a horned skeleton raising an hourglass \"toasting the Devil\" in its right hand.<ref name=nc /> In the skeleton's left hand, it held a spear pointing towards a red heart which had three drops of red blood below it, supposedly to signal that no quarter would be given.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/famous-pirates-and-their-flags-2136233|title=Who Are History's Most Famous Pirates and Their Flags?|first=Christopher |last=Minster |website=ThoughtCo|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> The historian E. T. Fox affirmed that this flag design would not have been of 18th-century pirate origin because, if the skeleton was meant to represent the Devil, then it would not have been a skeleton, and if it was supposed to represent [[Death (personification)|Death]], then it would not have been horned.<ref name=nc /> Most pirate flags at the time would have used simple imagery based on Christian symbols of mortality.<Ref name=nc />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Jolly Roger]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* Fox, E.T. (2015). ''Jolly Rogers, the True History of Pirate Flags''. {{ISBN|978-1-326-44817-2}}\n\n[[Category:Piracy]]\n[[Category:Maritime flags]]\n", "name_user": "97.118.60.75", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory:Removed content that was opinion based and not backed by sources or evidence.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flag_of_Blackbeard"}
